Logistic Regression and Random Forest using R on Kaggle’s Titanic dataset

22 August 2021

1. Background

Titanic - Machine Learning from Disaster is a long running competition on Kaggle, where we get to submit predictions on whether individuals onboard the vessel survive or die in the disaster.

This is a walkthrough using Logistic Regression and Random Forest with R as the scripting language. This prediction analysis includes more details than the previous one that I have provided in Python.

2. Methodology

We will do basic EDA, followed by hyperparameter tuning, and present the results at model level using the testing datatset.

3. Import

First, activate the necessary packages.

pacman::p_load(tidyverse, skimr, GGally,
               Hmisc, broom, DT,
               tidymodels, usemodels, doParallel)

Then import the various datasets from Kaggle.

titanic <- read_csv("train.csv")
titanic_test  <- read_csv("test.csv")
titanic_submission <- read_csv("gender_submission.csv")

Observations:

  • Name, Ticket and Cabin has 891, 681 and 147 unique values respectively. There will be a need to consider if these variables are needed in the model, and if needed, to reduce the unique values.
  • Missing values are observed in Cabin, Embarked, Age, which we need to apply imputation with K Nearest Neighbors. Imputation of the missing values will be performed.

To start off, we will create a clean dataset titanic2 with all the correct data types.

titanic2 <- titanic %>% 
  mutate(female = ifelse(Sex == "male", 0, 1),
         Survived = as.factor(Survived),
         Embarked = as.factor(Embarked),
         Embarked = as.numeric(Embarked),# 3=S, 2=Q, 1=C
         cabin_storey = str_extract(Cabin, pattern="^[:alpha:]"),
         cabin_storey = as.factor(cabin_storey),
         row_id = as.numeric(row_number())) %>% 
  select(-Name, -Sex, -Ticket, -PassengerId, -Cabin)

5. Data Split

We will split the titanic2 dataset into training and testing dataset next.

set.seed(090801)
titanic_split <- titanic2 %>%
  initial_split(prop=0.8,
                strata="Survived")

titanic_training <- training(titanic_split)
titanic_testing <- testing(titanic_split)

6. Create The Recipes

Create the dataset for use later on.

We will remove Name, Ticket and PassengerID, which does not seem to bear any relevance to the prediction.

As for Cabin, let’s include Cabin, as where the passengers are resting may have some correlation with their survival. We can gain insights by looking at the Cabin value e.g. A32 and referencing Layout of Titanic. It seems that the alphabet represents each storey and the numbers represent the unit numbers. We can extract the storey value and put into a new variable cabin_storey.

6.1 Main Recipe

reciped_A is created using all the variables, with Age as the polynomial term.

reciped_A <- recipe(formula = Survived ~ .,
                    data = titanic_training) %>% 
  step_rm(row_id) %>% 
  step_impute_knn(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  step_poly(Age,
            role = "predictor",
            degree = 2) %>% 
  step_dummy(cabin_storey)

Check that the arguments for reciped_A is set properly with prep() and bake().

baked_reciped_A <- reciped_A %>% 
  prep() %>% 
  bake(new_data = titanic_training)

We do a check on the significant interaction terms.

interact <- glm(Survived ~ (Pclass + Age + SibSp +

From the model with the interaction terms, we see thatPclass:female has a p-value of 0.000470, which is less than 0.05, hence we shall use this interaction term.

reciped_B is created using all the variables, with age as the polynomial term and female as the interaction term.

reciped_B <- recipe(formula = Survived ~ .,
                    data = titanic_training) %>% 
  step_rm(row_id) %>% 
  step_impute_knn(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_poly(Age,
            role = "predictor",
            degree = 2) %>% 
  step_interact(role = "predictor",
                terms = ~ Pclass:female) %>% 
  step_dummy(cabin_storey)

Check that the arguments for reciped_B is set properly with prep() and bake().

baked_reciped_B <- reciped_B %>% 
  prep() %>% 
  bake(new_data = titanic_training)

6.3 Recipe with correlation > 0.1

# use only those with correlation of more than 0.1
reciped_C <- recipe(formula = Survived ~ female +

7. Fit Model

Logistic Regression

model_LOGIT <- logistic_reg() %>%
  set_mode("classification") %>% 
  set_engine("glm")

Random Forest

model_RF <- rand_forest() %>% 
  set_mode("classification") %>% 
  set_engine("ranger",
             importance = "impurity") %>%
  set_args(mtry = tune(),
           trees = 1000)

8. Create Workflow

We will create the workflow for each permutation of recipe and model, in order to facilitate the tuning.

Logistic Regression

workflow_LOGIT_a <- workflow() %>% 
  add_recipe(reciped_A) %>% 
  add_model(model_LOGIT)

workflow_LOGIT_b <- workflow() %>% 
  add_recipe(reciped_B) %>% 
  add_model(model_LOGIT)

workflow_LOGIT_c <- workflow() %>% 
  add_recipe(reciped_C) %>% 
  add_model(model_LOGIT)

Random Forest

workflow_RF_a <- workflow() %>% 
  add_recipe(reciped_A) %>% 
  add_model(model_RF)

workflow_RF_b <- workflow() %>% 
  add_recipe(reciped_B) %>% 
  add_model(model_RF)

workflow_RF_c <- workflow() %>% 
  add_recipe(reciped_C) %>% 
  add_model(model_RF)

16. Evaluate Model Performance - Confusion Matrix

We will plot a confusion matrix to assess the model’s performance. We first create a function.

confusion_matrix_builder <- function(data, outcome) 
{
  
  {data} %>% 
    conf_mat({outcome}, .pred_class) %>% 
    pluck(1) %>% 
    as_tibble() %>% 
    mutate(cm_colors = ifelse(Truth == "1" & Prediction == "1", "True Positive",
                              ifelse(Truth == "1" & Prediction == "0", "False Negative",
                                     ifelse(Truth == "0" & Prediction == "1", "False Positive", 
                                            "True Negative")))) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(x = Prediction, y = Truth)) + 
    geom_tile(aes(fill = cm_colors), show.legend = F) +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("True Positive" = "lightgreen",
                                 "False Negative" = "pink",
                                 "False Positive" = "pink",
                                 "True Negative" = "lightgreen")) + 
    geom_text(aes(label = n), color = "white", size = 10) + 
    geom_label(aes(label = cm_colors), vjust = 2) + 
    ggthemes::theme_fivethirtyeight() + 
    theme(axis.title = element_text())
}

Logistic Regression

Recall that sensitivity is the metric that evaluates a model’s ability to predict true positives of each available category, while specificity determines a model’s ability to predict if an observation does not belong to a specific category.

confusion_matrix_builder(predictions_LOGIT, "Survived") +
  labs(title="Confusion Matrix for Logistic Regression Model",
       subtitle = "Sensitivity = 0.62; Specificity = 0.88")

Random Forest

confusion_matrix_builder(predictions_RF, "Survived") +
  labs(title="Confusion Matrix for Random Forest Model",
       subtitle = "Sensitivity = 0.65; Specificity = 0.93")

Random Forest model scores better than Logistic Regression in both Sensitivity and Specificity.

predictions_LOGIT_2 <- predictions_LOGIT%>%

predictions_RF_2 <- predictions_RF %>%

18. Variable Importance

As the random forest model is clearly more superior, we will utilize this model for the next plot on variable importance.

We will first save all the predictions into the finalized model. This is our ultimate model.

finalized_model <- finalized_workflow_RF_a %>% fit(titanic2)

We will then create a summary of the model.

summary_of_finalized_model <- extract_fit_parsnip(finalized_model)$fit

We then create the dataframe variable_importance to store the importance of the feature.

variable_importance <- data.frame(importance = summary_of_finalized_model$variable.importance) %>% 
  rownames_to_column("feature") %>% 
  as_tibble() %>% 
  mutate(feature = factor(feature))

We will then visualize the comparison of the features that are more significant.

variable_importance %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = importance, 
             y = reorder(feature, importance)
  )
  ) +
  geom_col(aes(fill = importance),
           show.legend = F) + 
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "tomato1", 
                      high = "tomato3") + 
  scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0, 0)
  ) + 
  ggthemes::theme_fivethirtyeight() + 
  labs(title = "Variable (Feature) Importance\nin Predicting Customer Attrition",
       subtitle = "We should pay more attention to gender, fare and age")

19. Predict on test dataset

Lastly, we shall predict using the test dataset given by Kaggle. We shall first modify the dataset do that the types are similar.

titanic_test2 <- titanic_test %>% 
  mutate(female = ifelse(Sex == "male", 0, 1),
         Embarked = as.factor(Embarked),
         Embarked = as.numeric(Embarked),# 3=S, 2=Q, 1=C
         cabin_storey = str_extract(Cabin, pattern="^[:alpha:]"),
         cabin_storey = as.factor(cabin_storey),
         row_id = as.numeric(row_number())) %>% 
  select(-Name, -Sex, -Ticket, -PassengerId, -Cabin)

We then predict on test data.

predictions <- titanic_test %>% 
  select(PassengerId) %>% 
  mutate(Survived = finalized_model %>% predict(titanic_test2),
         Survived = Survived$.pred_class)
